{"title_page": "Asbestos abatement", "text_new": "{{refimprove article|date=September 2018}}\n{{Globalize|date=September 2019}} \n[[File:FAC-roof-sheeting.JPG|right|thumb|Weathered fibrous asbestos sheeting showing loose fibres]]\n\nMany buildings contain [[asbestos]], which was used in spray-applied [[flame retardant]], thermal system insulation, and in a variety of other materials. Asbestos was sometimes \"[[Flocking (texture)|flocked]]\" above false ceilings, inside technical ducts, and in many other small spaces where firefighters would have difficulty gaining access. Structural components like asbestos panels were also used.  In residences, asbestos was often a component of a type of flocked acoustic ceiling called [[popcorn ceiling]] or \"cottage cheese ceiling\", until its production was banned in the US in 1978.  However, the ban allowed installers to use up remaining stocks, so houses built as late as 1986 could still have asbestos in their acoustic ceilings.{{cn|date=August 2014}}  The only way to be sure is to remove a sample and have it tested by a competent laboratory. \n\n==Rationale==\nDepending on how and where asbestos was applied, it might not pose any risk to most users of the building.  If the fibers cannot become dislodged, they cannot be inhaled, and thus the asbestos poses no risk. However, some methods of applying asbestos, particularly [[Flocking (texture)|flocking]], allow asbestos fibers to  gradually drop off into the air. Asbestos poses hazards to maintenance personnel who have to drill holes in walls for installation of cables or pipes. Even if the workers are [[ppe|protected]], such maintenance operation may release fibers into the air, which may be inhaled by others. Interventions in areas where asbestos is present often have to follow stringent procedures.\n\nWhen asbestos fibers can easily be made into airborne dust, the material is known as \"friable\". For example, a [[popcorn ceiling]] is extremely friable, whereas [[Vinyl composition tile|asbestos floor tile]] is considered non-friable.{{Citation needed|reason=evidence not provided by Vinyl tile link|date=January 2020}} Friable materials, such as popcorn ceiling tiles, have a lifespan between 20\u201340 years plus; whereas non-friable materials, such as asbestos roofing tiles, have a lifespan of 50\u2013100 years and beyond.   \n\nDifferent countries have different regulations and methods of enforcement, when it comes to asbestos removal. It is extremely important to remember that prior to any asbestos removal procedures taking place; the client has a duty of care and must verify that the specialist removal contractor can provide proof of the following:{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n*license if licensing is required within the jurisdiction\n*specific asbestos public and employer [[liability insurance]]\n*worker training to include supervisor and contract manager training within the past 12 months\n*worker fit-testing and medical surveillance within 12 months\n*specialist equipment testing within 6 months - DOP and PAT within the EU\n\nOptionally, the specialist contractor should be able to provide accreditation from [[ARCA]] or other such trade organization.{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Removal procedures==\n[[File:UK Asbestos Removal Enclosure.jpg|right|thumb|Typical UK temporary enclosure used for asbestos removal]]\n[[File:Asbestos-abatement-temporary-air-duct.jpg|right|thumb|A temporary plastic air duct used to exhaust filtered air from a negative air pressure (suction) machine|alt=A photo of a temporary plastic air duct that leads out from an area where asbestos abatement is taking place.]]\n[[File:Asbestos Removal 2008.JPG|thumb|right|An apartment complex that was subject to asbestos removal before [[demolition]]]]\nIn the United States, asbestos removal must be completed by an [[EPA]] licensed asbestos abatement contractor. Furthermore, the building has to be tested by an EPA licensed testing consultant. \n\nWhen asbestos abatement is taking place, occupants are not allowed to enter the area.  Typically, the part of the building from which asbestos is being removed has to be sealed off in order to prevent contamination of the other areas. Methods of sealing off an area often include the use of [[polyethylene]] film, [[duct tape]] and [[negative air pressure]] machines which are fitted with [[HEPA]] filters. The idea is that the contained area is pulling fresh air in as to not let asbestos fibers out into the surrounding environment.{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n\nOnly a special [[vacuum cleaner]] that is designed for asbestos containment (class H) can be safely used when cleaning up during and after asbestos removal.  Ordinary vacuum cleaners cannot be used, even those fitted with a HEPA filter.<ref>[http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/guidance/em4.pdf British government]</ref>  An ordinary vacuum cleaner will expel the asbestos fibres into the room air.\n\nIf the building is closed to normal users, it may be necessary to seal it off from outside atmosphere so that no accessible air is contaminated. Examples of buildings that required asbestos removal  include the [[Jussieu Campus]] and the [[Tour Montparnasse]].\n\nAn asbestos-containing building that is to be [[demolition|torn down]] may have to be sealed, and to have its asbestos safely removed before ordinary [[demolition]] can be performed.  The asbestos removal may take longer and cost more than the actual demolition. For example, the former seat of parliament of [[East Germany]], the [[Palast der Republik]], was stripped of most of its asbestos between 1998 and 2001, before it was finally demolished starting in 2006.\n\nNew innovative methods for asbestos removal have been used. One example is the [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]]\u2019s B238 building, where a track mounted wet cutting [[saw]] with a [[diamond blade]] was used in order to cut the building into small sections. These small sections were then double wrapped in plastic, the minimum requirement when transporting asbestos material, and driven to a [[landfill]]. This method not only contained the asbestos material within the [[gunite]] and metal layers of the walls, but also kept workers at a safe distance since the saw was [[Unmanned ground vehicle|controlled remotely]].<ref name=\"Open Air\">[https://www.dndkm.org/DOEKMDocuments/BestPractices/19-FINAL_%20EFCOG%20Best%20Practice%20002_Open%20Air%20Demolition%20of%20Asbestos%20Gunite.pdf Open Air Demolition of Asbestos Gunite by Using Track Mounted Wet Cutting Saw] dndkm.org</ref>\n\n==Alternatives to removal==\nRemoval is not the only means of Removal [http://www.aucoinsinsulation.com asbestos abatement]. Asbestos and asbestos-bearing materials may be \"enclosed\" or \"encapsulated\" to prevent building occupants from being exposed to the fibers.{{cn|date=April 2020<ref>www.aucoinsinsulation.com </ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n\n* [[Asbestine]]\n* [[Asbestos and the law]]\n* [[Fibro]]\n* [[Fireproofing]]\n* [[List of minerals]]\n* [[Mesothelioma]]\n* [[Vermiculite]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Asbestos|Abatement]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove article|date=September 2018}}\n{{Globalize|date=September 2019}} \n[[File:FAC-roof-sheeting.JPG|right|thumb|Weathered fibrous asbestos sheeting showing loose fibres]]\n\nMany buildings contain [[asbestos]], which was used in spray-applied [[flame retardant]], thermal system insulation, and in a variety of other materials. Asbestos was sometimes \"[[Flocking (texture)|flocked]]\" above false ceilings, inside technical ducts, and in many other small spaces where firefighters would have difficulty gaining access. Structural components like asbestos panels were also used.  In residences, asbestos was often a component of a type of flocked acoustic ceiling called [[popcorn ceiling]] or \"cottage cheese ceiling\", until its production was banned in the US in 1978.  However, the ban allowed installers to use up remaining stocks, so houses built as late as 1986 could still have asbestos in their acoustic ceilings.{{cn|date=August 2014}}  The only way to be sure is to remove a sample and have it tested by a competent laboratory. \n\n==Rationale==\nDepending on how and where asbestos was applied, it might not pose any risk to most users of the building.  If the fibers cannot become dislodged, they cannot be inhaled, and thus the asbestos poses no risk. However, some methods of applying asbestos, particularly [[Flocking (texture)|flocking]], allow asbestos fibers to  gradually drop off into the air. Asbestos poses hazards to maintenance personnel who have to drill holes in walls for installation of cables or pipes. Even if the workers are [[ppe|protected]], such maintenance operation may release fibers into the air, which may be inhaled by others. Interventions in areas where asbestos is present often have to follow stringent procedures.\n\nWhen asbestos fibers can easily be made into airborne dust, the material is known as \"friable\". For example, a [[popcorn ceiling]] is extremely friable, whereas [[Vinyl composition tile|asbestos floor tile]] is considered non-friable.{{Citation needed|reason=evidence not provided by Vinyl tile link|date=January 2020}} Friable materials, such as popcorn ceiling tiles, have a lifespan between 20\u201340 years plus; whereas non-friable materials, such as asbestos roofing tiles, have a lifespan of 50\u2013100 years and beyond.   \n\nDifferent countries have different regulations and methods of enforcement, when it comes to asbestos removal. It is extremely important to remember that prior to any asbestos removal procedures taking place; the client has a duty of care and must verify that the specialist removal contractor can provide proof of the following:{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n*license if licensing is required within the jurisdiction\n*specific asbestos public and employer [[liability insurance]]\n*worker training to include supervisor and contract manager training within the past 12 months\n*worker fit-testing and medical surveillance within 12 months\n*specialist equipment testing within 6 months - DOP and PAT within the EU\n\nOptionally, the specialist contractor should be able to provide accreditation from [[ARCA]] or other such trade organization.{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n\n==Removal procedures==\n[[File:UK Asbestos Removal Enclosure.jpg|right|thumb|Typical UK temporary enclosure used for asbestos removal]]\n[[File:Asbestos-abatement-temporary-air-duct.jpg|right|thumb|A temporary plastic air duct used to exhaust filtered air from a negative air pressure (suction) machine|alt=A photo of a temporary plastic air duct that leads out from an area where asbestos abatement is taking place.]]\n[[File:Asbestos Removal 2008.JPG|thumb|right|An apartment complex that was subject to asbestos removal before [[demolition]]]]\nIn the United States, asbestos removal must be completed by an [[EPA]] licensed asbestos abatement contractor. Furthermore, the building has to be tested by an EPA licensed testing consultant. \n\nWhen asbestos abatement is taking place, occupants are not allowed to enter the area.  Typically, the part of the building from which asbestos is being removed has to be sealed off in order to prevent contamination of the other areas. Methods of sealing off an area often include the use of [[polyethylene]] film, [[duct tape]] and [[negative air pressure]] machines which are fitted with [[HEPA]] filters. The idea is that the contained area is pulling fresh air in as to not let asbestos fibers out into the surrounding environment.{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n\nOnly a special [[vacuum cleaner]] that is designed for asbestos containment (class H) can be safely used when cleaning up during and after asbestos removal.  Ordinary vacuum cleaners cannot be used, even those fitted with a HEPA filter.<ref>[http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/guidance/em4.pdf British government]</ref>  An ordinary vacuum cleaner will expel the asbestos fibres into the room air.\n\nIf the building is closed to normal users, it may be necessary to seal it off from outside atmosphere so that no accessible air is contaminated. Examples of buildings that required asbestos removal  include the [[Jussieu Campus]] and the [[Tour Montparnasse]].\n\nAn asbestos-containing building that is to be [[demolition|torn down]] may have to be sealed, and to have its asbestos safely removed before ordinary [[demolition]] can be performed.  The asbestos removal may take longer and cost more than the actual demolition. For example, the former seat of parliament of [[East Germany]], the [[Palast der Republik]], was stripped of most of its asbestos between 1998 and 2001, before it was finally demolished starting in 2006.\n\nNew innovative methods for asbestos removal have been used. One example is the [[Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory]]\u2019s B238 building, where a track mounted wet cutting [[saw]] with a [[diamond blade]] was used in order to cut the building into small sections. These small sections were then double wrapped in plastic, the minimum requirement when transporting asbestos material, and driven to a [[landfill]]. This method not only contained the asbestos material within the [[gunite]] and metal layers of the walls, but also kept workers at a safe distance since the saw was [[Unmanned ground vehicle|controlled remotely]].<ref name=\"Open Air\">[https://www.dndkm.org/DOEKMDocuments/BestPractices/19-FINAL_%20EFCOG%20Best%20Practice%20002_Open%20Air%20Demolition%20of%20Asbestos%20Gunite.pdf Open Air Demolition of Asbestos Gunite by Using Track Mounted Wet Cutting Saw] dndkm.org</ref>\n\n==Alternatives to removal==\nRemoval is not the only means of asbestos abatement. Asbestos and asbestos-bearing materials may be \"enclosed\" or \"encapsulated\" to prevent building occupants from being exposed to the fibers.{{cn|date=August 2014}}\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n\n* [[Asbestine]]\n* [[Asbestos and the law]]\n* [[Fibro]]\n* [[Fireproofing]]\n* [[List of minerals]]\n* [[Mesothelioma]]\n* [[Vermiculite]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Asbestos|Abatement]]\n", "name_user": "216.181.255.67", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAlternatives to removal)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asbestos_abatement"}
{"title_page": "Block heater", "text_new": "{{short description|Heating system for internal combustion engines to assist in starting in cold weather. }}\n[[Image:topazBlockHeater.jpg|thumb|right|Electrical cord for powering a block heater]]\nA '''block heater''' is used in cold climates to warm an engine prior to starting. They are mostly used for car engines; however they have also been used in aircraft engines.\n\nThe most common design of block heater is an electrical heating element embedded in the engine block.\n\n== Purpose ==\nPre-heating of an engine is primarily used to make it easier to start.  Added benefits are:\n*The cabin heater produces heat sooner for comfort and to [[Defogger|de-fog]] the windscreen.<ref name=\"Anchorage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.muni.org/Departments/health/environment/AirQ/Pages/WhyPlug20F.aspx |title=Why plug at 20 degrees? |website=www.muni.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114212923/http://www.muni.org/Departments/health/environment/AirQ/Pages/WhyPlug20F.aspx |archivedate=14 January 2011}}</ref>\n*Reduction of condensation of fuel on cold cylinder walls during start thus\n** saving fuel and reducing [[Vehicle emissions control|exhaust emissions]] and \n** reducing oil dilution by gasoline scraped into the oil pan by the piston rings.\n*The engine reaches operating temperature sooner, so the engine does not run rich as long.  This further reduces fuel consumption and emissions.\n*Less load on the starter and battery thereby prolonging their service lives.\n*Less engine wear as oil circulation is improved.\n*Reduces the need for a [[Remote starter]], thereby further saving fuel and emissions.\n\nBlock heaters or coolant heaters are also found on the diesel engines in [[standby generator]]s, to reduce the time taken for the generator to reach full power output in an emergency.\n\n== Considerations ==\n* The car operator must have access to electrical power.  While this easily done at home, it is likely not available while travelling or while at work.  Nonetheless, the greatest need for a pre-heat is after the automobile or truck has cold soaked overnight.\n* Connection.  The operator needs to connect the cable after driving and disconnect before driving.  Most connectors are not designed to self-disconnect, so forgetting to disconnect can result in damage to the cables or the points on the car where the cable is mounted.  After a snow storm the cable may not be visible under the snow.\n* Energy cost.  The power used to heat the engine adds a cost.  However the savings in fuel generally outweigh this cost, especially if a timer is used to limit the heating period to about 4 hours before the expected start time.\n** Example cost: If electricity costs $0.08 per kWh and a 700W heater is used for 4 hours, the electrical cost is about $0.22.  The savings in fuel and wear and tear on the engine are greater than this.  On smaller engines, the block heaters are about 300W.  During the night and up to about 07:00 in the morning, electricity costs are at off-peak rates in many places further reducing the cost.\n\n== Designs ==\nSome cars are produced with block heaters from the factory, while others are fitted with block heaters as an aftermarket add-on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Using an Engine Heater in a Diesel Engine for Cold-Weather Starts |url=https://www.dummies.com/home-garden/car-repair/diesel-engines/using-an-engine-heater-in-a-diesel-engine-for-cold-weather-starts/ |website=www.dummies.com |accessdate=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The most common type of block heater is an electric heating element in the [[engine block]], which is connected through a power cord often routed through the vehicle's grille. Some block heaters are designed to replace one of the engine's [[core plug]]s and therefore heat the engine via the coolant.<ref>{{cite web |title=How cold should it be before I plug my car into a block heater? |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-drive/culture/commuting/what-is-the-benefit-of-plugging-in-my-car-to-a-block-heater-and-when-should-i-do-it/article27446878/ |website=www.theglobeandmail.com |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlternative methods of warming an engine include:<ref>{{cite web |title=Block Heater Technology: Unsung Hero of the Frozen North |url=https://www.lifewire.com/car-block-heater-frozen-north-534833 |website=www.lifewire.com |accessdate=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Engine oil heater attached to the engine's [[oil pan]] with magnets.\n* Engine oil heater inserted into the [[dipstick]] tube.\n* In-line coolant heaters, which are installed into a radiator hose to warm the coolant (sometimes with a circulation pump to increase its effectiveness).\n* Electric blankets that is laid over the top of the engine.\n\nElectric timers are often used with engine warmers, since it is only necessary to run the warmer for a few hours before starting the engine.<ref name=Anchorage/> Some cars pump hot coolant from the cooling system into a 3-litre insulated [[thermos]]-style reservoir at shutdown, where it stays warm for several days.<ref>{{cite web |title=In praise of the lowly block heater |url=https://www.metrompg.com/posts/block-heater.htm |website=www.metrompg.com |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Standheizung-Schweden.jpg|thumb|A parked car plugged in to an electrical outlet to power the block heater]]\nBlock heaters are frequently used in regions with cold winters such as the northern United States, Canada, Russia and Scandinavia. In some countries where block heaters are commonly used, carparks are sometimes fitted with electrical outlets for powering the block heaters.\n\nTesting in the 1970s of warm-up times for block heaters found little benefit in operating a block heater for more than four hours prior to starting a vehicle.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wiens |first1=E.H. |title=Automotive Engine Heaters |journal=Canadian Agricultural Engineering |date=June 1972 |pages=15-20 |url=http://www.csbe-scgab.ca/docs/journal/14/14_1_15_ocr.pdf |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> It was found that coolant temperature increased by almost {{convert|20|C-change|F-change|0|}} during the first four hours, regardless of the initial temperature. Four tests were run at ambient temperatures ranging from {{convert|-29|to|-11|C|F|0|abbr=on}}; continued use of the heater for up to two hours more only further increased the temperature by up to {{convert|3|C-change|F-change|0|abbr=on}}. Engine oil temperature was found to increase over these periods by just {{convert|5|C-change|F-change|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Car warmers, block heaters and energy controls |url=http://www.hydro.mb.ca/your_home/home_comfort/block_heaters.pdf |website=www.hydro.mb.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927134325/http://www.hydro.mb.ca/your_home/home_comfort/block_heaters.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAn early example of pre-heating piston engines prior to start-up was in the 1930s in Northern Canada, where aviators flew with flight engineers who were responsible for preparing the [[radial engine]]s for shutdown and startup to reduce the effects of subzero temperatures. The flight engineer was responsible for draining the oil into buckets at night, and preheating the engine and buckets of oil using a blanket wrapped around the engine and a device known as a blow pot \u2013 essentially a [[kerosene]] jet-heater used for several hours prior to flight.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bent Props & Blow Pots |url=http://www.harbourpublishing.com/title/BentPropsBlowPots |website=www.harbourpublishing.com |accessdate=30 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, German pilots could not stop the oil freezing in the engines of their [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]] planes because of the extreme cold first experienced in the [[Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)#Soviet_counter-offensive:_Winter_1941|1941 winter campaign]] in the Soviet Union. A captured Soviet airman showed them how pouring aviation fuel into the aircraft's oil sump would thaw the oil. Another solution, also learned from the Soviets, was to ignite fuel in the space around the engine.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |last=Kaplan\n  |first=Philip\n  |year=2007\n  |page=118\n  |title=Fighter Aces of the Luftwaffe in World War WWII\n  |location=Auldgirth, Dumfriesshire, UK\n  |publisher=Pen & Sword Aviation\n  |isbn=978-1-84415-460-9\n  |ref=harv\n}}</ref>\n\nAn early automotive use was the \"head bolt heater\", invented by [[Andrew Freeman (inventor)|Andrew Freeman]] in the United States and patented on 8 November 1949.<ref name=\"Anchorage\"/><ref name=Freeman>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prairiepublic.org/radio/dakota-datebook?post=6116 |title=Headbolt Heaters |access-date=2011-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721232350/http://www.prairiepublic.org/radio/dakota-datebook?post=6116 |archive-date=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Patent_49>{{US patent reference| number = 2487326 |y= 1949 |m= 11 |d= 08 |inventor= A. L. Freeman |title= Electric Internal-Combustion Engine Head Bolt Heater }}</ref> These early heaters replaced one of the engine's head bolts with a hollow, threaded shank containing a resistive heating element.<ref name=Patent_49/><ref name=Patent_51>{{US patent reference |number= 2611066|y= 1952 |m= 09 |d= 16 |inventor= A. L. Freeman |title= Electric Head Bolt Heater for Internal-Combustion Engines }}</ref> Before the block heater was introduced, people used a variety of methods to warm engines before starting them, such as pouring hot water on the engine block or draining the engine's oil for storage inside overnight. Some even shoveled embers underneath their vehicle's engine to obtain the same effect.<ref name=Freeman/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commonscat|Block heaters}}\n{{Automotive engine}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive electrics]]\n[[Category:Automotive engine technologies]]\n[[Category:Auto parts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Heating system for internal combustion engines to assist in starting in cold weather. }}\n[[Image:topazBlockHeater.jpg|thumb|right|Electrical cord for powering a block heater]]\nA '''block heater''' is used in cold climates to warm an engine prior to starting. They are mostly used for car engines, however they have also been used in aircraft engines.\n\nThe most common design of block heater is an electrical heating element embedded in the engine block.\n\n== Purpose ==\nPre-heating of an engine is primarily used to make it easier to start.  Added benefits are:\n*The cabin heater produces heat sooner for comfort and to [[Defogger|de-fog]] the windscreen.<ref name=\"Anchorage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.muni.org/Departments/health/environment/AirQ/Pages/WhyPlug20F.aspx |title=Why plug at 20 degrees? |website=www.muni.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114212923/http://www.muni.org/Departments/health/environment/AirQ/Pages/WhyPlug20F.aspx |archivedate=14 January 2011}}</ref>\n*Reduction of condensation of fuel on cold cylinder walls during start thus\n** saving fuel and reducing [[Vehicle emissions control|exhaust emissions]] and \n** reducing oil dilution by gasoline scraped into the oil pan by the piston rings.\n*The engine reaches operating temperature sooner, so the engine does not run rich as long.  This further reduces fuel consumption and emissions.\n*Less load on the starter and battery thereby prolonging their service lives.\n*Less engine wear as oil circulation is improved.\n*Reduces the need for a [[Remote starter]], thereby further saving fuel and emissions.\n\nBlock heaters or coolant heaters are also found on the diesel engines in [[standby generator]]s, to reduce the time taken for the generator to reach full power output in an emergency.\n\n== Considerations ==\n* The car operator must have access to electrical power.  While this easily done at home, it is likely not available while travelling or while at work.  Nonetheless, the greatest need for a pre-heat is after the automobile or truck has cold soaked overnight.\n* Connection.  The operator needs to connect the cable after driving and disconnect before driving.  Most connectors are not designed to self-disconnect, so forgetting to disconnect can result in damage to the cables or the points on the car where the cable is mounted.  After a snow storm the cable may not be visible under the snow.\n* Energy cost.  The power used to heat the engine adds a cost.  However the savings in fuel generally outweigh this cost, especially if a timer is used to limit the heating period to about 4 hours before the expected start time.\n** Example cost: If electricity costs $0.08 per kWh and a 700W heater is used for 4 hours, the electrical cost is about $0.22.  The savings in fuel and wear and tear on the engine are greater than this.  On smaller engines, the block heaters are about 300W.  During the night and up to about 07:00 in the morning, electricity costs are at off-peak rates in many places further reducing the cost.\n\n== Designs ==\nSome cars are produced with block heaters from the factory, while others are fitted with block heaters as an aftermarket add-on.<ref>{{cite web |title=Using an Engine Heater in a Diesel Engine for Cold-Weather Starts |url=https://www.dummies.com/home-garden/car-repair/diesel-engines/using-an-engine-heater-in-a-diesel-engine-for-cold-weather-starts/ |website=www.dummies.com |accessdate=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The most common type of block heater is an electric heating element in the [[engine block]], which is connected through a power cord often routed through the vehicle's grille. Some block heaters are designed to replace one of the engine's [[core plug]]s and therefore heat the engine via the coolant.<ref>{{cite web |title=How cold should it be before I plug my car into a block heater? |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-drive/culture/commuting/what-is-the-benefit-of-plugging-in-my-car-to-a-block-heater-and-when-should-i-do-it/article27446878/ |website=www.theglobeandmail.com |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlternative methods of warming an engine include:<ref>{{cite web |title=Block Heater Technology: Unsung Hero of the Frozen North |url=https://www.lifewire.com/car-block-heater-frozen-north-534833 |website=www.lifewire.com |accessdate=27 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* Engine oil heater attached to the engine's [[oil pan]] with magnets.\n* Engine oil heater inserted into the [[dipstick]] tube.\n* In-line coolant heaters, which are installed into a radiator hose to warm the coolant (sometimes with a circulation pump to increase its effectiveness).\n* Electric blankets that is laid over the top of the engine.\n\nElectric timers are often used with engine warmers, since it is only necessary to run the warmer for a few hours before starting the engine.<ref name=Anchorage/> Some cars pump hot coolant from the cooling system into a 3-litre insulated [[thermos]]-style reservoir at shutdown, where it stays warm for several days.<ref>{{cite web |title=In praise of the lowly block heater |url=https://www.metrompg.com/posts/block-heater.htm |website=www.metrompg.com |accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Standheizung-Schweden.jpg|thumb|A parked car plugged in to an electrical outlet to power the block heater]]\nBlock heaters are frequently used in regions with cold winters such as the northern United States, Canada, Russia and Scandinavia. In some countries where block heaters are commonly used, carparks are sometimes fitted with electrical outlets for powering the block heaters.\n\nTesting in the 1970s of warm-up times for block heaters found little benefit in operating a block heater for more than four hours prior to starting a vehicle.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wiens |first1=E.H. |title=Automotive Engine Heaters |journal=Canadian Agricultural Engineering |date=June 1972 |pages=15-20 |url=http://www.csbe-scgab.ca/docs/journal/14/14_1_15_ocr.pdf |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> It was found that coolant temperature increased by almost {{convert|20|C-change|F-change|0|}} during the first four hours, regardless of the initial temperature. Four tests were run at ambient temperatures ranging from {{convert|-29|to|-11|C|F|0|abbr=on}}; continued use of the heater for up to two hours more only further increased the temperature by up to {{convert|3|C-change|F-change|0|abbr=on}}. Engine oil temperature was found to increase over these periods by just {{convert|5|C-change|F-change|0|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Car warmers, block heaters and energy controls |url=http://www.hydro.mb.ca/your_home/home_comfort/block_heaters.pdf |website=www.hydro.mb.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927134325/http://www.hydro.mb.ca/your_home/home_comfort/block_heaters.pdf |archivedate=27 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAn early example of pre-heating piston engines prior to start-up was in the 1930s in Northern Canada, where aviators flew with flight engineers who were responsible for preparing the [[radial engine]]s for shutdown and startup to reduce the effects of subzero temperatures. The flight engineer was responsible for draining the oil into buckets at night, and preheating the engine and buckets of oil using a blanket wrapped around the engine and a device known as a blow pot \u2013 essentially a [[kerosene]] jet-heater used for several hours prior to flight.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bent Props & Blow Pots |url=http://www.harbourpublishing.com/title/BentPropsBlowPots |website=www.harbourpublishing.com |accessdate=30 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War II, German pilots could not stop the oil freezing in the engines of their [[Messerschmitt Bf 109]] planes because of the extreme cold first experienced in the [[Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)#Soviet_counter-offensive:_Winter_1941|1941 winter campaign]] in the Soviet Union. A captured Soviet airman showed them how pouring aviation fuel into the aircraft's oil sump would thaw the oil. Another solution, also learned from the Soviets, was to ignite fuel in the space around the engine.<ref>{{Cite book\n  |last=Kaplan\n  |first=Philip\n  |year=2007\n  |page=118\n  |title=Fighter Aces of the Luftwaffe in World War WWII\n  |location=Auldgirth, Dumfriesshire, UK\n  |publisher=Pen & Sword Aviation\n  |isbn=978-1-84415-460-9\n  |ref=harv\n}}</ref>\n\nAn early automotive use was the \"head bolt heater\", invented by [[Andrew Freeman (inventor)|Andrew Freeman]] in the United States and patented on 8 November 1949.<ref name=\"Anchorage\"/><ref name=Freeman>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prairiepublic.org/radio/dakota-datebook?post=6116 |title=Headbolt Heaters |access-date=2011-03-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721232350/http://www.prairiepublic.org/radio/dakota-datebook?post=6116 |archive-date=2015-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Patent_49>{{US patent reference| number = 2487326 |y= 1949 |m= 11 |d= 08 |inventor= A. L. Freeman |title= Electric Internal-Combustion Engine Head Bolt Heater }}</ref> These early heaters replaced one of the engine's head bolts with a hollow, threaded shank containing a resistive heating element.<ref name=Patent_49/><ref name=Patent_51>{{US patent reference |number= 2611066|y= 1952 |m= 09 |d= 16 |inventor= A. L. Freeman |title= Electric Head Bolt Heater for Internal-Combustion Engines }}</ref> Before the block heater was introduced, people used a variety of methods to warm engines before starting them, such as pouring hot water on the engine block or draining the engine's oil for storage inside overnight. Some even shoveled embers underneath their vehicle's engine to obtain the same effect.<ref name=Freeman/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commonscat|Block heaters}}\n{{Automotive engine}}\n\n[[Category:Automotive electrics]]\n[[Category:Automotive engine technologies]]\n[[Category:Auto parts]]\n", "name_user": "Wurdnurd2", "label": "safe", "comment": "comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Block_heater"}
{"title_page": "Death of Aniah Blanchard", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| image    = Aniah_Blanchard_Event_Infobox.jpg\n| caption  = Family photo of Blanchard (left). Blanchard in the Chevron gas station before her disappearance (right). \n| date     = October 2019\n| location = [[Alabama, United States]]\n| reported deaths  = Aniah Blanchard\n| arrests          = Three (charges against two suspects were dismissed) \n| suspects          =  Ibraheem Yazeed                  \n|charges           = [[Capital murder]] & [[kidnapping]]\n}}\nThe '''death of Aniah Blanchard''' occurred in the fall of 2019. Blanchard, the 19-year-old stepdaughter of [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] fighter [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]], was reported missing on October 24. \nShe had last been seen at the Chevron Gas Station in [[Auburn, Alabama]] the previous night. A witness from the gas station claims to have seen Blanchard being [[Kidnapping|kidnapped]]. \nBlanchard's body was found in [[Macon County, Alabama]] one month after her disappearance.<ref name= \":1\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.cbs42.com/remembering-aniah/timeline-of-aniah-blanchard-disappearance/ |title = Timeline of Aniah Blanchard kidnapping case |first = Drew |last = Taylor |date = November 15, 2019 |website = cbs42.com }}</ref> The cause of death was determined to be a gunshot wound.<ref name= \":2\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mma/2019/12/03/aniah-blanchard-death-ibraheem-yazeed-capital-murder-charge/2596353001/ |title = Lead suspect in death of UFC fighter's stepdaughter to face capital murder charge |first = Brian |last = Lyman |date = December 3, 2019 |website = usatoday.com }}</ref> A suspect, identified as Ibraheem Yazeed, was [[arrested]] and [[Criminal charge|charged]] with Blanchard's [[murder]]. As of April 2020, Yazeed is being held in Lee County Jail without bond and has a preliminary hearing scheduled for June 3.<ref name= \":3\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.alabamanews.net/2020/04/09/suspect-in-murder-of-aniah-blanchard-has-his-preliminary-hearing-delayed/ |title = Suspect in Murder of Aniah Blanchard Has His Preliminary Hearing Delayed |date = April 9, 2020 |website = alabamanews.net }}</ref> [[Prosecutors]] are seeking the [[death penalty]].<ref name= \":7\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/03/aniah-blanchard-murdered-stepdaughter-ufc-fighter/ |title = He allegedly kidnapped and murdered a UFC fighter's stepdaughter. Prosecutors want the death penalty |first = Katie |last = Shepherd |date = December 3, 2019 |website = washingtonpost.com }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/aniah-blanchard-story-update-ibraheem-yazeed-charged-with-capital-murder-today-2019-12-02/ |title = Suspect charged with capital murder in Aniah Blanchard's death |first = Victoria |last = Albert |date = December 2, 2019 |website = cbsnews.com }}</ref>\n\nBlanchard's death attracted national attention and media coverage<ref name= \":4\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.wftv.com/news/deep-viral/aniah-blanchard-3rd-man-charged-as-remains-found-in-missing-student-search/1012846357/ |title = Aniah Blanchard: DNA confirms remains found are those of missing Alabama college student |first = Crystal |last = Bonvillian |date = November 27, 2019 |website = wftv.com }}</ref><ref name= \":5\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.fox8live.com/2019/11/25/remains-believed-be-missing-student-aniah-blanchard-found-da-says/ |title = Missing student Aniah Blanchard's remains possibly found |date = November 25, 2019 |website = fox8live.com }}</ref>\nand led to the creation of \"Aniah's Law\" which reforms [[Alabama]]'s [[bail]] system.<ref name= \":6\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/aniahs-law-on-alabama-bail-reform-moves-step-closer-to-passing.html |title = Aniah's Law on Alabama bail reform moves step closer to passing |first = Mike |last = Carson |date = March 11, 2020 |website = al.com }}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance, investigation, and arrests==\nBlanchard was reported missing to the Auburn Police Department on October 24, 2019.<ref name= \":8\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2019/11/07/aniah-blanchard-missing-auburn-teen-alabama-timeline-disappearance/2516399001/ |title = Aniah Blanchard timeline: What we know about the disappearance, search for Alabama teen |first = Grace |last = Pateras |date = November 7, 2019 |website = montgomeryadvertiser.com }}</ref>\nShe had last been seen by a family member on the evening of October 23 and had reportedly told a friend over the phone about plans to see a man she had met on a dating app.<ref name= \":1\"/>\nJust before midnight, Blanchard's roommate received Snapchat messages indicating that Blanchard was with a man. Blanchard's roommate and parents found this behavior to be \"uncharacteristic\" and it is unclear if Blanchard herself had, in fact, sent the messages.<ref name= \":8\"/> Surveillance video showed Blanchard in the Chevron Gas Station in Auburn in the late-night hours of October 23.<ref name= \":7\"/><ref name= \":9\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.alabamanews.net/2019/11/25/update-investigators-on-scene-in-macon-county-in-aniah-blanchard-case/ |title = Update: Investigators on Scene in Macon County in Aniah Blanchard Case |date = November 25, 2019 |website = alabamanews.net }}</ref>\n\nBlanchard's disappearance resulted in an extensive effort to locate her. By October 30, a task force of several law enforcement agencies including the [[FBI]], the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and the Alabama Department of Forensic Sciences, was formed.<ref name= \":8\"/> The disappearance and the subsequent effort to find Blanchard received national media coverage.<ref name= \":5\"/> On October 25, authorities found Blanchard's damaged vehicle.<ref name= \":10\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.wsfa.com/2019/10/29/timeline-aniah-blanchards-disappearance/ |title = Timeline of Aniah Blanchard's disappearance |first = Samantha |last = Day |date = October 28, 2019 |website = wsfa.com }}</ref> The black 2017 Honda CRV had been abandoned near an apartment complex in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]] and contained evidence of \"foul play\"--specifically, blood in the front passenger's seat. The blood, which was confirmed by the Alabama Department of Forensic Sciences to be that of Blanchard, \"was indicative of someone suffering a life-threatening injury.\"<ref name= \":11\">{{Cite web |url = https://abcnews.go.com/US/witness-suspect-force-aniah-blanchard-missing-stepdaughter-ufc/story?id=66872047 |title = Witness said he saw suspect force Aniah Blanchard, missing stepdaughter of UFC fighter, into car against her will: Affidavit |first = Mark |last = Osborne |date = November 9, 2019 |website = abcnews.go.com }}</ref><ref name= \":12\">{{Cite web |url = https://nypost.com/2019/11/11/blood-of-ufc-stars-missing-stepdaughter-aniah-blanchard-found-inside-car/ |title = Blood of UFC star's missing stepdaughter Aniah Blanchard found inside car |first = Lee |last = Brown |date = November 11, 2019 |website = nypost.com }}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, the Auburn Police Department released an image from a surveillance video of a \"person of interest.\" The following day, the person of interest was identified as 29-year-old Ibraheem Yazeed of Montgomery.  Surveillance video showed that he was in the store at the same time as Blanchard.  He is seen buying alcohol and looking in Blanchard's direction.<ref name= \":1\"/>\nHe was also captured exiting the passenger side of Blanchard's vehicle. Surveillance video from another gas station shows him re-entering the passenger's side of her car.\nIn addition to surveillance footage, a witness allegedly saw Blanchard and Yazeed interacting outside the store near her car.<ref name= \":13\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/aniah-blanchard-fought-for-her-life-before-she-was-killed |title = Aniah Blanchard's Alleged Killer Said She 'Went For The Gun,' While Apparently Trying To Fight Him Off, Witness Says |first = Jill |last = Sederstrom |date = December 6, 2019 |website = oxygen.com }}</ref>\nThe witness also claims to have seen him force her into the car against her will and then leave with her in the vehicle.<ref name= \":11\"/><ref name= \":14\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/11/witness-saw-aniah-blanchard-abducted-from-outside-auburn-store-records-state.html |title = Witness saw Aniah Blanchard abducted from outside Auburn store, records state |first = Carol |last = Robinson |date = November 9, 2019 |website = al.com }}</ref>\nAccording to detectives, the witness told a companion about the event but was told to mind his business.<ref name= \":1\"/>\nYazeed allegedly told another witness that he had Blanchard's vehicle, but would not allow the witness to see Blanchard at that time. The witness also claims that Yazeed said he shot a girl and that she \"went for the gun.\"<ref name= \":13\"/> At the time of Blanchard's death, Yazeed was free on a $295,000 bond. He had been charged with possession of marijuana, [[robbery]], kidnapping, and [[attempted murder]].<ref name= \":15\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ufc/2019/11/27/aniah-blanchard-dead-remains-identified-macon-county-alabama/4322207002/ |title = Remains confirmed to belong to UFC fighter's stepdaughter Aniah Blanchard |first1 = Kirsten |last1 = Fiscus |first2 = Melissa |last2 = Brown |date = November 27, 2019 |website = usatoday.com }}</ref>\nThe charges are connected to an alleged crime in January 2019, during which four assailants robbed and beat two men in a hotel in Montgomery. One of the victims, a 77-year-old man, was reportedly left  \"unconscious, unresponsive, severely injured and near death.\"<ref name= \":16\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/opinion/2019/11/authorities-must-answer-why-aniah-blanchards-kidnapper-was-out-on-bond.html |title = Authorities must answer why Aniah Blanchard's kidnapper was out on bond |first = Rachel |last = Bryars |date = November 18, 2019 |website = al.com }}</ref><ref name= \":17\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/08/us/auburn-missing-teen-aniah-blanchard-arrest/index.html |title = A man has been arrested in last month's disappearance of Aniah Blanchard |first1 = Madeline |last1 = Holcombe, |first2 = Steve |last2 = Almasy |first3 = Mallika |last3 = Kallingal |date = November 8, 2019 |website = cnn.com }}</ref> The suspect is also accused of attempting to kill two police officers in 2012 by ramming his car into theirs and was arrested in 2017 for [[aggravated]] [[Battery (crime)|battery]] on a police officer.<ref name= \":16\"/>\n\nOn November 7, police issued an [[arrest warrant]] for Yazeed on suspicion of first-degree kidnapping.<ref name= \":17\"/>\nA tip led police to [[Pensacola, Florida]]<ref name= \":18\">{{Cite web |url = https://abcnews.go.com/US/funeral-held-aniah-blanchard-alabama-remember-slain-teens/story?id=67867716 |title = Memorial service held for Aniah Blanchard in Alabama to remember slain teen's 'light' |first1 = Christina |last = Carrega |date = December 21, 2019 |website = abcnews.go.com }}</ref>\nand the Florida Regional Fugitive Task Force located him near [[Interstate 10 in Alabama|Interstate 10]]'s Pine Forest Road exit. The suspect fled on foot and refused to comply with Marshall's verbal commands, leading them to \"physically remove him from his hiding spot.\" He was taken to the Escambia County Jail<ref name= \":14\"/> and subsequently agreed to be extradited back to Alabama.<ref name= \":17\"/> He has been held in the Lee County Jail without bond since then.<ref name= \":3\"/> He was moved to solitary confinement after his attorneys filed court documents claiming that he was facing death threats. A [[judge]] has determined that there is enough [[probable cause]] to proceed to [[grand jury]] hearings. The judge also issued a [[gag order]] preventing Yazeed's attorneys, prosecutors, and witnesses from speaking to the media about the case.<ref name= \":1\"/>\n\nOn November 22,  police arrested Antwain \"Squirmy\" Fisher, alleging that he disposed of evidence and provided transportation for Yazeed.<ref name= \":8\"/> Fisher had previously served three years in prison for his part in a drug-deal related murder.<ref name= \":1\"/> On November 25, police arrested a third suspect, David Johnson Jr., and charged him with hindering prosecution.<ref name= \":8\"/>\nCharges against Fisher and Johnson were later dismissed. In regards to the dismissal of Fisher's charges, District Attorney Brandon Hughes stated that \"it was determined that Mr. Fisher's conduct did not rise to the level of accomplice liability as was originally charged and as is required under Alabama law.\"<ref name= \":19\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/12/kidnapping-charge-dismissed-against-1-suspect-in-aniah-blanchard-case.html |title = Kidnapping charge dismissed against 1 suspect in Aniah Blanchard case |first = Carol |last = Robinson |date = December 18, 2019 |website = al.com }}</ref>\n\nOn November 25, human remains were found in Macon County, in the woods off County Road 2. On November 27, they were identified as Blanchard's.<ref name= \":1\"/><ref name= \":15\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.foxnews.com/us/remains-found-in-alabama-confirmed-as-that-of-missing-college-student |title = Remains found in Alabama confirmed as that of missing college student |first = Talia |last = Kaplan |date = November 27, 2019 |website = foxnews.com }}</ref> An [[autopsy]] determined that Blanchard was killed by a [[gunshot wound]].<ref name= \":2\"/> The charges against Yazeed were then upgraded from first-degree kidnapping to [[capital murder]].<ref name= \":1\"/> He currently faces two counts of capital murder, one for committing a murder in a car through the use of a deadly weapon while the victim is in a vehicle, and the other for committing a murder during a kidnapping in the first degree.<ref name= \":3\"/> District Attorney Hughes's office is seeking the death penalty.<ref name= \":20\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/02/us/aniah-blanchard-charges-upgraded/index.html |title = Charges upgraded to murder for suspect in Aniah Blanchard case |first1 = Jamiel |last1 = Lynch |first2 = Melissa |last2 = Gray |date = December 3, 2019 |website = cnn.com }}</ref> A preliminary hearing was scheduled for March. It was later moved to April but was again postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]]. A hearing is currently scheduled for June 3.<ref name= \":3\"/>\n\n==Victim==\n{{Infobox person\n| caption            = Aniah Blanchard\n|name                = Aniah Blanchard\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|2000|07|22}}\n| disappeared_date   = October 23, 2019\n| disappeared_place  = [[Auburn, Alabama]]\n| death_date         = 2019\n| death_cause        = [[Gunshot wound]]\n| body_discovered    = November 25, 2019\n| alma_mater         = [[Southern Union State Community College]] \n| home_town          = [[Homewood, Alabama]]\n| mother             = Angela Haley-Harris\n| father             = Elijah Blanchard\n| relatives          = [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]] (stepfather)\n}}\nAniah Haley Blanchard (born July 22, 2000) was from Homewood, Alabama.<ref name= \":21\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2019/11/14/aniah-blanchard-update-family-stories-missing-auburn-teen/2563965001/ |title = Aniah Blanchard's family still hears the voice and laughter of their 'baby girl' |first = Safiya |last = Charles |date = November 14, 2019 |website = usatoday.com }}</ref><ref name= \":22\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/10/aniah-blanchards-father-missing-teens-disappearance-is-devastating.html/ |title = Aniah Blanchard's father: Missing teen's disappearance is 'devastating' |first = Carol |last = Robinsons |date = October 28, 2019 |website = al.com }}</ref> She is the daughter of Elijah Blanchard, a [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] businessman<ref name= \":23\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.albugle.com/news/2019/11/11/natalee-holloways-mother-joins-search-for-aniah-blanchard/ |title = Natalee Holloway's mother joins search for Aniah Blanchard |first = Carol |last = Robinsons |date = November 11, 2019 |website = albugle.com }}</ref> and Angela Haley-Harris, a registered nurse. Haley-Harris is married to UFC [[heavyweight]] fighter Walt Harris.<ref name= \":21\"/> Blanchard graduated from [[Homewood High School]] where she played softball.<ref name= \":22\"/><ref name= \":24\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/11/04/aniah-haley-blanchard-missing-what-to-know-know-about-alabama-teen-disappearance/4127613002/ |title = 'A heart of gold': Aniah Blanchard's father pleads 'we want her home' |first = Melissa |last = Brown |date = November 4, 2019 |website = montgomeryadvertiser.com }}</ref> At the time of her death, she was a student at [[Southern Union State Community College]] and was studying early childhood education. She planned on transferring to [[Auburn University]].<ref name= \":10\"/><ref name= \":18\"/>\nA scholarship in Blanchard's memory has been established by [[Homewood City School District|Homewood Public Schools]].<ref name= \":18\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBlanchard's disappearance and death attracted national attention and media coverage.<ref name= \":5\"/><ref name= \":25\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.wbrc.com/2019/12/04/suspect-aniah-blanchard-case-faces-second-capital-murder-charge/ |title = Suspect in Aniah Blanchard case faces second capital murder charge |date = December 4, 2019 |website = wbrc.com }}</ref><ref name= \":26\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.wbrc.com/2019/11/26/full-timeline-disappearance-aniah-blanchard/ |title = Full timeline of the disappearance of Aniah Blanchard |first = Alex |last = Jones |date = November 26, 2019 |website = wbrc.com }}</ref><ref name= \":27\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.wtvm.com/2020/03/04/preliminary-hearing-set-april-aniah-blanchard-case/ |title = Preliminary hearing set for April in Aniah Blanchard case |date = March 4, 2020 |website = wtvm.com }}</ref><ref name= \":28\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.boston25news.com/news/deep-viral/aniah-blanchard-3rd-man-charged-as-remains-found-in-missing-student-search/1012846232/ |title = Aniah Blanchard: DNA confirms remains found are those of missing Alabama college student |first = Crystal |last = Bonvillian |date = November 27, 2019 |website = boston25news }}</ref> Governor [[Kay Ivey]] issued a proclamation authorizing a $5,000 reward for information leading to an arrest and conviction. UFC president [[Dana White]] pledged an additional $25,000 to Ivey's award and an anonymous source offered $5,000.<ref name= \":29\">{{Cite web |url = https://abcnews.go.com/US/alabama-authorities-foul-play-involved-missing-college-student/story?id=66633708 |title = Evidence found in car of UFC star's missing stepdaughter indicates foul play, police say |first = Karma |last = Allen |date = October 31, 2019 |website = abcnews.go.com }}</ref>\nThe reward later rose to over 105,000, with much of the money coming from the UFC and UFC supporters.<ref name= \":1\"/>\n\nBlanchard's death led to the creation of Aniah's law, which reforms Alabama's bail laws. [[Constitution of Alabama|Alabama's Constitution]] guarantees the right to bail for all defendants except those charged with capital offenses. Aniah's Law would expand the exception to other serious crimes including [[arson]], [[burglary]], [[domestic violence]], aggravated [[child abuse]], [[assault]], robbery, kidnapping, [[human trafficking]], [[rape]], sodomy, [[Torture|sexual torture]], [[terrorism]], and murder. Prosecutors would be allowed to request a hearing regarding bail which a judge could grant or deny. If the hearing is held the defendant would be allowed to testify, present witnesses, and cross-examine witnesses. The judge could choose to either allow or deny bail.<ref name= \":30\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/2020/02/alabama-bail-reform-bill-called-aniahs-law-advances-in-house.html |title = Alabama bail reform bill called Aniah's Law advances in House |first = Mike |last = Carson |date = February 19, 2020 |website = al.com }}</ref>\nBlanchard's parents and step-parents have spoken to legislators in support of the proposed law. In February 2020, the [[Alabama House of Representatives]] voted 104-0 in favor of Aniah's law.<ref name= \":31\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.al.com/news/2020/02/alabama-house-considers-bail-denial-for-violent-charges.html |title = Alabama House passes Aniah's Law for bail reform |first = Mike |last = Carson |date = February 27, 2020 |website = al.com }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox event\n| image    = Aniah_Blanchard_Event_Infobox.jpg\n| caption  = Family photo of Blanchard (left). Blanchard in the Chevron gas station before her disappearance (right). \n| date     = October, 2019\n| location = [[Alabama, United States]]\n| reported deaths  = Aniah Blanchard\n| arrests          = Three (charges against two suspects were dismissed) \n| suspects          =  Ibraheem Yazeed                  \n|charges           = [[Capital murder]] & [[kidnapping]]\n}}\nThe '''death of Aniah Blanchard''' occurred in the fall of 2019. Blanchard, the 19-year-old stepdaughter of [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] fighter [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]], was reported missing on October 24. \nShe had last been seen at the Chevron Gas Station in [[Auburn, Alabama]] the previous night. A witness from the gas station claims to have seen Blanchard being [[Kidnapping|kidnapped]]. \nBlanchard\u2019s body was found in [[Macon County, Alabama]] one month after her disappearance.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs42.com/remembering-aniah/timeline-of-aniah-blanchard-disappearance/|title=Timeline of Aniah Blanchard kidnapping case|first=Drew|last=Taylor|date=November 15, 2019|website=cbs42.com}}</ref> The cause of death was determined to be a gunshot wound.<ref name= \u201c:2\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mma/2019/12/03/aniah-blanchard-death-ibraheem-yazeed-capital-murder-charge/2596353001/|title=Lead suspect in death of UFC fighter's stepdaughter to face capital murder charge|first=Brian|last=Lyman|date=December 3, 2019|website=usatoday.com}}</ref> A suspect, identified as Ibraheem Yazeed, was [[arrested]] and [[Criminal charge|charged]] with Blanchard\u2019s [[murder]]. As of April 2020, Yazeed is being held in Lee County Jail without bond and has a preliminary hearing scheduled for June 3.<ref name= \u201c:3\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamanews.net/2020/04/09/suspect-in-murder-of-aniah-blanchard-has-his-preliminary-hearing-delayed/|title=Suspect in Murder of Aniah Blanchard Has His Preliminary Hearing Delayed|date=Apr 9, 2020|website=alabamanews.net}}</ref> [[Prosecutors]] are seeking the [[death penalty]].<ref name= \u201c:7\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/12/03/aniah-blanchard-murdered-stepdaughter-ufc-fighter/|title=He allegedly kidnapped and murdered a UFC fighter\u2019s stepdaughter. Prosecutors want the death penalty|first=Katie |last=Shepherd|date=December 3, 2019|website=washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/aniah-blanchard-story-update-ibraheem-yazeed-charged-with-capital-murder-today-2019-12-02/|title=Suspect charged with capital murder in Aniah Blanchard's death|first=Victoria|last=Albert|date=December 2, 2019|website=cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\nBlanchard's death attracted national attention and media coverage<ref name= \u201c:4\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wftv.com/news/deep-viral/aniah-blanchard-3rd-man-charged-as-remains-found-in-missing-student-search/1012846357/|title=Aniah Blanchard: DNA confirms remains found are those of missing Alabama college student|first= Crystal|last= Bonvillian|date=November 27, 2019|website=wftv.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:5\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fox8live.com/2019/11/25/remains-believed-be-missing-student-aniah-blanchard-found-da-says/|title=Missing student Aniah Blanchard\u2019s remains possibly found|date=November 25, 2019|website=fox8live.com}}</ref>\nand led to the creation of \u201cAniah\u2019s Law\u201d which reforms [[Alabama]]\u2019s [[bail]] system.<ref name= \u201c:6\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/03/aniahs-law-on-alabama-bail-reform-moves-step-closer-to-passing.html|title=Aniah\u2019s Law on Alabama bail reform moves step closer to passing|first=Mike|last=Carson|date=Mar 11, 2020|website=al.com}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance, investigation, and arrests==\nBlanchard was reported missing to the Auburn Police Department on October 24, 2019.<ref name= \u201c:8\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2019/11/07/aniah-blanchard-missing-auburn-teen-alabama-timeline-disappearance/2516399001/|title=Aniah Blanchard timeline: What we know about the disappearance, search for Alabama teen|first=Grace|last=Pateras|date= November 7, 2019|website=montgomeryadvertiser.com}}</ref>\nShe had last been seen by a family member on the evening of October 23 and had reportedly told a friend over the phone about plans to see a man she had met on a dating app.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/>\nJust before midnight, Blanchard\u2019s roommate received Snapchat messages indicating that Blanchard was with a man. Blanchard\u2019s roommate and parents found this behavior to be \u201cuncharacteristic\u201d and it is unclear if Blanchard herself had, in fact, sent the messages.<ref name= \u201c:8\u201d/> Surveillance video showed Blanchard in the Chevron Gas Station in Auburn in the late-night hours of October 23.<ref name= \u201c:7\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:9\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alabamanews.net/2019/11/25/update-investigators-on-scene-in-macon-county-in-aniah-blanchard-case/|title=Update: Investigators on Scene in Macon County in Aniah Blanchard Case|date= November 25, 2019|website=alabamanews.net}}</ref>\n\nBlanchard\u2019s disappearance resulted in an extensive effort to locate her. By October 30, a task force of several law enforcement agencies including the [[FBI]], the [[Department of Homeland Security]], and the Alabama Department of Forensic Sciences, was formed.<ref name= \u201c:8\u201d/> The disappearance and the subsequent effort to find Blanchard received national media coverage.<ref name= \u201c:5\u201d/> On October 25, authorities found Blanchard\u2019s damaged vehicle.<ref name= \u201c:10\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsfa.com/2019/10/29/timeline-aniah-blanchards-disappearance/|title=Timeline of Aniah Blanchard\u2019s disappearance|first=Samantha|last=Day|date= October 28, 2019|website=wsfa.com}}</ref> The black 2017 Honda CRV had been abandoned near an apartment complex in [[Montgomery, Alabama|Montgomery]] and contained evidence of \u201cfoul play\u201d--specifically, blood in the front passenger's seat. The blood, which was confirmed by the Alabama Department of Forensic Sciences to be that of Blanchard, \u201cwas indicative of someone suffering a life-threatening injury.\u201d<ref name= \u201c:11\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/witness-suspect-force-aniah-blanchard-missing-stepdaughter-ufc/story?id=66872047|title=Witness said he saw suspect force Aniah Blanchard, missing stepdaughter of UFC fighter, into car against her will: Affidavit|first=Mark|last=Osborne|date= November 9, 2019|website=abcnews.go.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:12\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/11/blood-of-ufc-stars-missing-stepdaughter-aniah-blanchard-found-inside-car/|title=Blood of UFC star\u2019s missing stepdaughter Aniah Blanchard found inside car|first=Lee|last=Brown|date= November 11, 2019|website=nypost.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, the Auburn Police Department released an image from a surveillance video of a \u201cperson of interest.\u201d The following day, the person of interest was identified as 29-year-old Ibraheem Yazeed of Montgomery.  Surveillance video showed that he was in the store at the same time as Blanchard.  He is seen buying alcohol and looking in Blanchard\u2019s direction.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/>\nHe was also captured exiting the passenger side of Blanchard\u2019s vehicle. Surveillance video from another gas station shows him re-entering the passenger's side of her car.\nIn addition to surveillance footage, a witness allegedly saw Blanchard and Yazeed interacting outside the store near her car.<ref name= \u201c:13\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/aniah-blanchard-fought-for-her-life-before-she-was-killed|title=Aniah Blanchard's Alleged Killer Said She 'Went For The Gun,' While Apparently Trying To Fight Him Off, Witness Says|first=Jill|last=Sederstrom|date= December 6, 2019|website=oxygen.com}}</ref>\nThe witness also claims to have seen him force her into the car against her will and then leave with her in the vehicle.<ref name= \u201c:11\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:14\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/11/witness-saw-aniah-blanchard-abducted-from-outside-auburn-store-records-state.html|title=Witness saw Aniah Blanchard abducted from outside Auburn store, records state|first=Carol|last=Robinson|date= November 9, 2019|website=al.com}}</ref>\nAccording to detectives, the witness told a companion about the event but was told to mind his business.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/>\nYazeed allegedly told another witness that he had Blanchard\u2019s vehicle, but would not allow the witness to see Blanchard at that time. The witness also claims that Yazeed said he shot a girl and that she \u201cwent for the gun.\u201d<ref name= \u201c:13\u201d/> At the time of Blanchard\u2019s death, Yazeed was free on a $295,000 bond. He had been charged with possession of marijuana, [[robbery]], kidnapping, and [[attempted murder]].<ref name= \u201c:15\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ufc/2019/11/27/aniah-blanchard-dead-remains-identified-macon-county-alabama/4322207002/|title=Remains confirmed to belong to UFC fighter's stepdaughter Aniah Blanchard|first1=Kirsten|last1=Fiscus|first2=Melissa|last2=Brown|date= November 27, 2019|website=usatoday.com}}</ref>\nThe charges are connected to an alleged crime in January of 2019, during which four assailants robbed and beat two men in a hotel in Montgomery. One of the victims, a 77-year-old man, was reportedly left  \u201cunconscious, unresponsive, severely injured and near death.\"<ref name= \u201c:16\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/opinion/2019/11/authorities-must-answer-why-aniah-blanchards-kidnapper-was-out-on-bond.html |title=Authorities must answer why Aniah Blanchard\u2019s kidnapper was out on bond|first=Rachel|last= Bryars|date= November 18, 2019|website=al.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:17\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/11/08/us/auburn-missing-teen-aniah-blanchard-arrest/index.html|title=A man has been arrested in last month's disappearance of Aniah Blanchard|first1=Madeline|last1=Holcombe, |first2=Steve|last2=Almasy|first3=Mallika|last3=Kallingal|date= November 8, 2019|website=cnn.com}}</ref> The suspect is also accused of attempting to kill two police officers in 2012 by ramming his car into theirs and was arrested in 2017 for [[aggravated]] [[Battery (crime)|battery]] on a police officer.<ref name= \u201c:16\u201d/>\n\nOn November 7, police issued an [[arrest warrant]] for Yazeed on suspicion of first-degree kidnapping.<ref name= \u201c:17\u201d/>\nA tip led police to [[Pensacola, Florida]]<ref name= \u201c:18\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/funeral-held-aniah-blanchard-alabama-remember-slain-teens/story?id=67867716|title=Memorial service held for Aniah Blanchard in Alabama to remember slain teen's 'light'|first1=Christina|last=Carrega|date= December 21, 2019|website=abcnews.go.com}}</ref>\nand the Florida Regional Fugitive Task Force located him near [[Interstate 10]]\u2019s Pine Forest Road exit. The suspect fled on foot and refused to comply with Marshall\u2019s verbal commands, leading them to \u201cphysically remove him from his hiding spot.\u201d He was taken to the Escambia County Jail<ref name= \u201c:14\u201d/> and subsequently agreed to be extradited back to Alabama.<ref name= \u201c:17\u201d/> He has been held in the Lee County Jail without bond since then.<ref name= \u201c:3\u201d/> He was moved to solitary confinement after his attorneys filed court documents claiming that he was facing death threats. A [[judge]] has determined that there is enough [[probable cause]] to proceed to [[grand jury]] hearings. The judge also issued a [[gag order]] preventing Yazeed\u2019s attorneys, prosecutors, and witnesses from speaking to the media about the case.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/>\n\nOn November 22,  police arrested Antwain \u201cSquirmy\u201d Fisher, alleging that he disposed of evidence and provided transportation for Yazeed.<ref name= \u201c:8\u201d/> Fisher had previously served three years in prison for his part in a drug-deal related murder.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/> On November 25, police arrested a third suspect, David Johnson Jr., and charged him with hindering prosecution.<ref name= \u201c:8\u201d/>\nCharges against Fisher and Johnson were later dismissed. In regards to the dismissal of Fisher\u2019s charges, District Attorney Brandon Hughes stated that \u201cit was determined that Mr. Fisher\u2019s conduct did not rise to the level of accomplice liability as was originally charged and as is required under Alabama law.\u201d<ref name= \u201c:19\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/12/kidnapping-charge-dismissed-against-1-suspect-in-aniah-blanchard-case.html|title=Kidnapping charge dismissed against 1 suspect in Aniah Blanchard case\n|first=Carol|last=Robinson|date= December 18, 2019|website=al.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 25, human remains were found in Macon County, in the woods off County Road 2. On November 27, they were identified as Blanchard\u2019s.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:15\u201d/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/remains-found-in-alabama-confirmed-as-that-of-missing-college-student|title=Remains found in Alabama confirmed as that of missing college student|first=Talia|last=Kaplan|date=November 27, 2019|website=foxnews.com}}</ref> An [[autopsy]] determined that Blanchard was killed by a [[gunshot wound]].<ref name= \u201c:2\u201d/> The charges against Yazeed were then upgraded from first-degree kidnapping to [[capital murder]].<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/> He currently faces two counts of capital murder, one for committing a murder in a car through the use of a deadly weapon while the victim is in a vehicle, and the other for committing a murder during a kidnapping in the first degree.<ref name= \u201c:3\u201d/> District Attorney Hughes's office is seeking the death penalty.<ref name= \u201c:20\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/02/us/aniah-blanchard-charges-upgraded/index.html|title=Charges upgraded to murder for suspect in Aniah Blanchard case\n|first1=Jamiel|last1=Lynch|first2=Melissa|last2=Gray|date= December 3, 2019|website=cnn.com}}</ref> A preliminary hearing was scheduled for March. It was later moved to April but was again postponed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]]. A hearing is currently scheduled for June 3.<ref name= \u201c:3\u201d/>\n\n==Victim==\n{{Infobox person\n| caption            = Aniah Blanchard\n|name                = Aniah Blanchard\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|2000|07|22}}\n| disappeared_date   = October 23, 2019\n| disappeared_place  = [[Auburn, Alabama]]\n| death_date         = 2019\n| death_cause        = [[Gunshot wound]]\n| body_discovered    = November 25, 2019\n| alma_mater         = [[Southern Union State Community College]] \n| home_town          = [[Homewood, Alabama]]\n| mother             = Angela Haley-Harris\n| father             = Elijah Blanchard\n| relatives          = [[Walt Harris (fighter)|Walt Harris]] (stepfather)\n}}\nAniah Haley Blanchard (born July 22, 2000) was from Homewood, Alabama.<ref name= \u201c:21\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2019/11/14/aniah-blanchard-update-family-stories-missing-auburn-teen/2563965001/|title=Aniah Blanchard's family still hears the voice and laughter of their 'baby girl'|first=Safiya|last=Charles|date= November 14, 2019|website=usatoday.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:22\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2019/10/aniah-blanchards-father-missing-teens-disappearance-is-devastating.html/|title=Aniah Blanchard\u2019s father: Missing teen\u2019s disappearance is \u2018devastating\u2019\n|first=Carol|last=Robinsons|date= October 28, 2019|website=al.com}}</ref> She is the daughter of Elijah Blanchard, a [[Birmingham, Alabama|Birmingham]] businessman<ref name= \u201c:23\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.albugle.com/news/2019/11/11/natalee-holloways-mother-joins-search-for-aniah-blanchard/|title=Natalee Holloway\u2019s mother joins search for Aniah Blanchard|first=Carol|last=Robinsons|date= November 11, 2019|website=albugle.com}}</ref> and Angela Haley-Harris, a registered nurse. Haley-Harris is married to UFC [[heavyweight]] fighter Walt Harris.<ref name= \u201c:21\u201d/> Blanchard graduated from [[Homewood High School]] where she played softball.<ref name= \u201c:22\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:24\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/crime/2019/11/04/aniah-haley-blanchard-missing-what-to-know-know-about-alabama-teen-disappearance/4127613002/|title='A heart of gold': Aniah Blanchard's father pleads 'we want her home'|first=Melissa|last=Brown|date= November 4, 2019|website=montgomeryadvertiser.com}}</ref> At the time of her death, she was a student at [[Southern Union State Community College]] and was studying early childhood education. She planned on transferring to [[Auburn University]].<ref name= \u201c:10\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:18\u201d/>\nA scholarship in Blanchard\u2019s memory has been established by [[Homewood City School District|Homewood Public Schools]].<ref name= \u201c:18\u201d/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBlanchard\u2019s disappearance and death attracted national attention and media coverage.<ref name= \u201c:5\u201d/><ref name= \u201c:25\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2019/12/04/suspect-aniah-blanchard-case-faces-second-capital-murder-charge/ |title=Suspect in Aniah Blanchard case faces second capital murder charge|date= December 4, 2019 |website=wbrc.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:26\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2019/11/26/full-timeline-disappearance-aniah-blanchard/ |title=Full timeline of the disappearance of Aniah Blanchard|first=Alex|last=Jones|date=November 26,  2019 |website=wbrc.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:27\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtvm.com/2020/03/04/preliminary-hearing-set-april-aniah-blanchard-case/|title=Preliminary hearing set for April in Aniah Blanchard case|date=March 4, 2020 |website=wtvm.com}}</ref><ref name= \u201c:28\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boston25news.com/news/deep-viral/aniah-blanchard-3rd-man-charged-as-remains-found-in-missing-student-search/1012846232/|title=Aniah Blanchard: DNA confirms remains found are those of missing Alabama college student|first=Crystal|last=Bonvillian|date=November 27, 2019|website=boston25news}}</ref> Governor [[Kay Ivey]] issued a proclamation authorizing a $5,000 reward for information leading to an arrest and conviction. UFC president [[Dana White]] pledged an additional $25,000 to Ivey\u2019s award and an anonymous source offered $5,000.<ref name= \u201c:29\u201d>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://abcnews.go.com/US/alabama-authorities-foul-play-involved-missing-college-student/story?id=66633708|title=\nEvidence found in car of UFC star's missing stepdaughter indicates foul play, police say|first=Karma|last=Allen|date=October 31, 2019|website=abcnews.go.com}}</ref>\nThe reward later rose to over 105,000, with much of the money coming from the UFC and UFC supporters.<ref name= \u201c:1\u201d/>\n\nBlanchard\u2019s death led to the creation of Aniah\u2019s law, which reforms Alabama\u2019s bail laws. [[Constitution of Alabama|Alabama\u2019s Constitution]] guarantees the right to bail for all defendants except those charged with capital offenses. Aniah\u2019s Law would expand the exception to other serious crimes including [[arson]], [[burglary]], [[domestic violence]], aggravated [[child abuse]], [[assault]], robbery, kidnapping, [[human trafficking]], [[rape]], sodomy, [[Torture|sexual torture]], [[terrorism]], and murder. Prosecutors would be allowed to request a hearing regarding bail which a judge could grant or deny. If the hearing is held the defendant would be allowed to testify, present witnesses, and cross-examine witnesses. The judge could choose to either allow or deny bail.<ref name= \u201c:30\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/02/alabama-bail-reform-bill-called-aniahs-law-advances-in-house.html|title=Alabama bail reform bill called Aniah\u2019s Law advances in House|first=Mike|last=Carson|date=February 19, 2020|website=al.com}}</ref>\nBlanchard\u2019s parents and step-parents have spoken to legislators in support of the proposed law. In February 2020, the [[Alabama House of Representatives]] voted 104-0 in favor of Aniah\u2019s law.<ref name= \u201c:31\u201d>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2020/02/alabama-house-considers-bail-denial-for-violent-charges.html|title=\nAlabama House passes Aniah\u2019s Law for bail reform|first=Mike|last=Carson|date=February 27, 2020|website=al.com}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Imzadi1979", "label": "safe", "comment": "harmonize whitespace in citation templates (usingRegex citation formatter); date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript; other basic formatting fixes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Death_of_Aniah_Blanchard"}
{"title_page": "Madeleine Lebeau", "text_new": "{{short description|French actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Madeleine Lebeau\n| image         = Madeleine Lipo.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       =\n| birthname     = Marie Madeleine Berthe Lebeau\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1923|06|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Antony, Hauts-de-Seine|Antony]], France<ref name=\"Grimes\">{{cite news |last=Grimes |first=William |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/17/movies/madeleine-lebeau-casablanca-actress-dies-at-92.html |title=Madeleine Lebeau, \u2018Casablanca' Actress, Dies at 92 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=16 May 2016 |accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2016|05|1|1923|06|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Estepona]], Spain\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1939\u20131970\n| notable_works = ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', ''[[8\u00bd]]''\n| spouse        = {{plain list|\n*{{marriage|[[Marcel Dalio]]|end=div.|1939|1942}}\n*{{marriage|[[Tullio Pinelli]]|end=died|1988|2009}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Marie Madeleine Berthe Lebeau''' (10 June 1923 \u2013 1 May 2016) was a French film actress.\n\n==Early life==\nLebeau married actor [[Marcel Dalio]] in 1939; it was his second marriage. They had met while performing a play together. She had already appeared in her first film, an uncredited role as a student in the melodrama ''[[Girls in Distress|Young Girls in Trouble]]'' (''Jeunes filles en d\u00e9tresse'', 1939).<ref name=\"Grimes\"/> In June 1940, Lebeau and Dalio (who was Jewish) fled Paris ahead of the invading [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] and reached [[Lisbon]]. They are presumed to have received transit visas from [[Aristides de Sousa Mendes]], allowing them to enter Spain and journey on to Portugal. It took them two months to obtain visas to Chile.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16/>\n\nHowever, when their ship, the [[S.S. Quanza|S.S. ''Quanza'']], stopped in Mexico, they were stranded, along with around 200 other passengers, when the Chilean visas they had purchased turned out to be forgeries. Eventually, they were able to get temporary Canadian passports and entered the United States.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16/> Lebeau made her Hollywood debut in ''[[Hold Back the Dawn]]'' (1941), which featured [[Charles Boyer]] and [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the leading roles. The following year, she appeared in the [[Errol Flynn]] movie ''[[Gentleman Jim (1942 film)|Gentleman Jim]]'', a biography of Irish-American boxer [[James J. Corbett]].<ref name=holly/>\n\nLebeau learned English during a seven-week stay with Dalio on a Portuguese freighter that was seeking a port for landing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Harrison|title=Behind the Scenes in Hollywood|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17084658/madeleine_lebeau/|work=The Call-Leader|date=March 29, 1941|location=Indiana, Elwood|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = February 2, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==''Casablanca''==\nLater that year she was cast in the role of Yvonne, [[Humphrey Bogart]]'s character's discarded mistress, in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''. [[Warner Bros.]] signed her to a $100-a-week contract for twenty-six weeks to be in a number of films. On 22 June, while she was filming her scenes in ''Casablanca'', her husband, Marcel Dalio, who played Emil the croupier in the same film, filed for divorce in [[Los Angeles]] on the grounds of desertion. They divorced in 1942. Shortly before the release of the film, Warner Bros. terminated her contract. After  [[Joy Page]] died in April 2008, Lebeau was the last surviving credited cast member of ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36295621 |title=Last surviving Casablanca actress Madeleine Lebeau dies |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe told [[Charlotte Chandler]], author of a biography of female lead [[Ingrid Bergman]], in the 1990s: \"It wasn't that I was cut out, it was because they kept changing the script, and each time they changed it, I had less of a part\". \"It was not personal, but I was so disappointed\".<ref name=\"Grimes\"/>\n\nLebeau's best moments in ''Casablanca'' are during the scene when French nationals sing \"The Marseillaise\" drowning out the group of German soldiers singing \"Die Wacht am Rhein\". The camera captures the (genuine) tears on her face, and later at the end of the anthem when she cries out ''Vive la France''. France had fallen to Nazi forces, and many of the actors performing in the scene were real-life refugees from Europe.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/madeleine-lebeau-french-actress-had-big-moment-in-casablanca/article30049529/ |title=Madeleine LeBeau: French actress had big moment in Casablanca |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |first1=Frances |last1=D'Emilio |first2=Lindsey |last2=Bahr |accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==After ''Casablanca''==\nFollowing ''Casablanca'', Lebeau appeared in two further American films. The first was a large role in the war drama ''[[Paris After Dark]]'' (1943), with her former husband. The following year, Lebeau had a smaller role in ''[[Music for Millions]]''. She appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in the play ''The French Touch'' in a production directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Clair]].<ref name=\"Grimes\"/> After the end of [[World War II]], Lebeau returned to France and continued her acting career. She appeared in ''[[The Royalists|Les Chouans]]'' (''The Royalists'', 1947) and worked in [[Great Britain]], appearing in a film with [[Jean Simmons]], ''[[Cage of Gold]]'' (1950).<ref name=bbc/>\n\n==Later years==\nShe would appear in 20 more films, mainly French, including ''[[La Parisienne (film)|La Parisienne]]'' (1957), with [[Brigitte Bardot]] as the star, as well as in [[Federico Fellini]]'s ''[[8\u00bd]]'' (1963). Lebeau's last two films were Spanish productions in 1965.<ref name=bbc/>\n\nIn 1988, she married her third husband, Italian screenwriter [[Tullio Pinelli]] who had contributed to the script of ''8\u00bd''.<ref name=holly/>\n\n===Death===\nLebeau died on 1 May 2016 in [[Estepona]], Spain, aged 92, after breaking her thigh bone.<ref name=holly>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Mike |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/madeleine-lebeau-dead-casablanca-actress-894113 |title=Madeleine Lebeau, Rick's Discarded Lover in 'Casablanca', Dies at 92 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=14 May 2016 |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> French culture minister [[Audrey Azoulay]] said of Madelaine Lebeau after her death: \"She was a free woman who lived by her own rules, totally inhabiting the roles entrusted to her by leading directors. She will forever be the face of French resistance.\"<ref name=\"Grimes\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1939 || ''Jeunes filles en d\u00e9tresse'' (''[[Girls in Distress]]'') || Une \u00e9l\u00e8ve de la pension || Uncredited\n|-\n| 1941 || ''[[Hold Back the Dawn]]'' || Anni ||\n|-\n| 1942 || ''[[Gentleman Jim (film)|Gentleman Jim]]'' || Anna Held ||\n|-\n| 1942 || ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' || Yvonne ||\n|-\n| 1943 || ''[[Paris After Dark]]''|| Collette ||\n|-\n| 1944 || ''[[Music for Millions]]'' || Jane ||\n|-\n| 1947 || ''[[The Royalists]]'' || Marie de Verneuil ||\n|-\n| 1948 || ''Le secret de Monte-Cristo'' (''The Secret of Monte-Cristo'') || Marguerite Vigouroux ||\n|-\n| 1950 || ''[[Cage of Gold]]'' || Marie ||\n|-\n| 1950 || ''Et moi j'te dis qu'elle t'a fait d'l'oeil!'' || Aur\u00e9lie Lambrusque ||\n|-\n| 1951 || ''[[Sins of Madeleine]]'' || Malou ||\n|-\n| 1951 || ''[[Paris Still Sings]]'' || Gis\u00e8le ||\n|-\n| 1952 || ''Fortun\u00e9 de Marseille'' || Tonia ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''L'\u00e9trange amazone'' || Eliane ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''Mandat d'amener'' || Fran\u00e7oise Delanglade ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''[[L\u00e9g\u00e8re et court v\u00eatue]]'' (''Lightly and Shortly Dressed'') || Jacqueline Lorette / Kiki ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''L'aventuri\u00e8re du Tchad '' (''[[The Adventurer of Chad]]'') || Fanny Lacour ||\n|-\n| 1954 || ''Si Versailles m'\u00e9tait cont\u00e9'' (''[[Royal Affairs in Versailles]]'') || Une dame de la cour || Uncredited\n|-\n| 1954 || ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Quai des blondes|fr}}'' || Nelly ||\n|-\n| 1954 || ''Cadet Rousselle'' || Marguerite de Beaufort ||\n|-\n| 1955 || ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1955 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'' || Emilie Pellapra ||\n|-\n| 1955 || ''La p\u00edcara molinera'' || Jacqueline ||\n|-\n| 1956 || ''Le pays d'o\u00f9 je viens'' (''The Country I Come From'') || Adrienne Terreau ||\n|-\n| 1957 || ''[[La Parisienne (film)|La Parisienne]]''|| Monique Wilson ||\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[La Vie \u00e0 deux]]'' (''Life for Two'') || Peggy ||\n|-\n| 1959 || ''Vous n'avez rien \u00e0 d\u00e9clarer?'' || Gloria Frontignac ||\n|-\n| 1959 || ''Le chemin des \u00e9coliers'' (''[[Way of Youth]]'') || Flora ||\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[8\u00bd]]'' || Madeleine, the French actress ||\n|-\n| 1964 || ''[[Desaf\u00edo en R\u00edo Bravo]]'' (''Gunmen of the Rio Grande'') || Jennie Lee ||\n|-\n| 1964 || ''[[Ang\u00e9lique, Marquise des Anges]]'' || La Grande Demoiselle ||\n|-\n| 1965 || ''La vuelta'' || ||\n|-\n| 1967 || ''La bouqueti\u00e8re des innocents'' || Marie de M\u00e9dicis || TV movie\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{AllMovie name}}\n* {{TCMDb name|110551}}\n* {{BFI|4ce2ba26f3e0e}}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebeau, Madeleine}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:French film actresses]]\n[[Category:French expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:People from Antony, Hauts-de-Seine]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Spain]]\n[[Category:French expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Madeleine Lebeau\n| image         = Madeleine Lipo.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       =\n| birthname     = Marie Madeleine Berthe Lebeau\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1923|06|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Antony, Hauts-de-Seine|Antony]], France<ref name=\"Grimes\">{{cite news |last=Grimes |first=William |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/17/movies/madeleine-lebeau-casablanca-actress-dies-at-92.html |title=Madeleine Lebeau, \u2018Casablanca' Actress, Dies at 92 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=16 May 2016 |accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|2016|05|1|1923|06|10}}\n| death_place   = [[Estepona]], Spain\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1939\u20131970\n| notable_works = ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'', ''[[8\u00bd]]''\n| spouse        = {{plain list|\n*{{marriage|[[Marcel Dalio]]|end=div.|1939|1942}}\n*{{marriage|[[Tullio Pinelli]]|end=died|1988|2009}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Marie Madeleine Berthe Lebeau''' (10 June 1923 \u2013 1 May 2016) was a French film actress.\n\n==Early life==\nLebeau married actor [[Marcel Dalio]] in 1939; it was his second marriage. They had met while performing a play together. She had already appeared in her first film, an uncredited role as a student in the melodrama ''[[Girls in Distress|Young Girls in Trouble]]'' (''Jeunes filles en d\u00e9tresse'', 1939).<ref name=\"Grimes\"/> In June 1940, Lebeau and Dalio (who was Jewish) fled Paris ahead of the invading [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] and reached [[Lisbon]]. They are presumed to have received transit visas from [[Aristides de Sousa Mendes]], allowing them to enter Spain and journey on to Portugal. It took them two months to obtain visas to Chile.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16/>\n\nHowever, when their ship, the [[S.S. Quanza|S.S. ''Quanza'']], stopped in Mexico, they were stranded, along with around 200 other passengers, when the Chilean visas they had purchased turned out to be forgeries. Eventually, they were able to get temporary Canadian passports and entered the United States.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16/> Lebeau made her Hollywood debut in ''[[Hold Back the Dawn]]'' (1941), which featured [[Charles Boyer]] and [[Olivia de Havilland]] in the leading roles. The following year, she appeared in the [[Errol Flynn]] movie ''[[Gentleman Jim (1942 film)|Gentleman Jim]]'', a biography of Irish-American boxer [[James J. Corbett]].<ref name=holly/>\n\nLebeau learned English during a seven-week stay with Dalio on a Portuguese freighter that was seeking a port for landing.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Harrison|title=Behind the Scenes in Hollywood|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/17084658/madeleine_lebeau/|work=The Call-Leader|date=March 29, 1941|location=Indiana, Elwood|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = February 2, 2018}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==''Casablanca''==\nLater that year she was cast in the role of Yvonne, [[Humphrey Bogart]]'s character's discarded mistress, in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''. [[Warner Bros.]] signed her to a $100-a-week contract for twenty-six weeks to be in a number of films. On 22 June, while she was filming her scenes in ''Casablanca'', her husband, Marcel Dalio, who played Emil the croupier in the same film, filed for divorce in [[Los Angeles]] on the grounds of desertion. They divorced in 1942. Shortly before the release of the film, Warner Bros. terminated her contract. After  [[Joy Page]] died in April 2008, Lebeau was the last surviving credited cast member of ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]''.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36295621 |title=Last surviving Casablanca actress Madeleine Lebeau dies |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nShe told [[Charlotte Chandler]], author of a biography of female lead [[Ingrid Bergman]], in the 1990s: \"It wasn't that I was cut out, it was because they kept changing the script, and each time they changed it, I had less of a part\". \"It was not personal, but I was so disappointed\".<ref name=\"Grimes\"/>\n\nLebeau's best moments in ''Casablanca'' are during the scene when French nationals sing \"The Marseillaise\" drowning out the group of German soldiers singing \"Die Wacht am Rhein\". The camera captures the (genuine) tears on her face, and later at the end of the anthem when she cries out ''Vive la France''. France had fallen to Nazi forces, and many of the actors performing in the scene were real-life refugees from Europe.<ref name=G&M-2016-05-16>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/film/madeleine-lebeau-french-actress-had-big-moment-in-casablanca/article30049529/ |title=Madeleine LeBeau: French actress had big moment in Casablanca |newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]] |first1=Frances |last1=D'Emilio |first2=Lindsey |last2=Bahr |accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==After ''Casablanca''==\nFollowing ''Casablanca'', Lebeau appeared in two further American films. The first was a large role in the war drama ''[[Paris After Dark]]'' (1943), with her former husband. The following year, Lebeau had a smaller role in ''[[Music for Millions]]''. She appeared on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in the play ''The French Touch'' in a production directed by [[Ren\u00e9 Clair]].<ref name=\"Grimes\"/> After the end of [[World War II]], Lebeau returned to France and continued her acting career. She appeared in ''[[The Royalists|Les Chouans]]'' (''The Royalists'', 1947) and worked in [[Great Britain]], appearing in a film with [[Jean Simmons]], ''[[Cage of Gold]]'' (1950).<ref name=bbc/>\n\n==Later years==\nShe would appear in 20 more films, mainly French, including ''[[La Parisienne (film)|La Parisienne]]'' (1957), with [[Brigitte Bardot]] as the star, as well as in [[Federico Fellini]]'s ''[[8\u00bd]]'' (1963). Lebeau's last two films were Spanish productions in 1965.<ref name=bbc/>\n\nIn 1988, she married her third husband, Italian screenwriter [[Tullio Pinelli]] who had contributed to the script of ''8\u00bd''.<ref name=holly/>\n\n===Death===\nLebeau died on 1 May 2016 in [[Estepona]], Spain, aged 92, after breaking her thigh bone.<ref name=holly>{{cite news |last=Barnes |first=Mike |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/madeleine-lebeau-dead-casablanca-actress-894113 |title=Madeleine Lebeau, Rick's Discarded Lover in 'Casablanca', Dies at 92 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=14 May 2016 |accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> French culture minister [[Audrey Azoulay]] said of Madelaine Lebeau after her death: \"She was a free woman who lived by her own rules, totally inhabiting the roles entrusted to her by leading director. She will forever be the face of French resistance.\"<ref name=\"Grimes\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1939 || ''Jeunes filles en d\u00e9tresse'' (''[[Girls in Distress]]'') || Une \u00e9l\u00e8ve de la pension || Uncredited\n|-\n| 1941 || ''[[Hold Back the Dawn]]'' || Anni ||\n|-\n| 1942 || ''[[Gentleman Jim (film)|Gentleman Jim]]'' || Anna Held ||\n|-\n| 1942 || ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' || Yvonne ||\n|-\n| 1943 || ''[[Paris After Dark]]''|| Collette ||\n|-\n| 1944 || ''[[Music for Millions]]'' || Jane ||\n|-\n| 1947 || ''[[The Royalists]]'' || Marie de Verneuil ||\n|-\n| 1948 || ''Le secret de Monte-Cristo'' (''The Secret of Monte-Cristo'') || Marguerite Vigouroux ||\n|-\n| 1950 || ''[[Cage of Gold]]'' || Marie ||\n|-\n| 1950 || ''Et moi j'te dis qu'elle t'a fait d'l'oeil!'' || Aur\u00e9lie Lambrusque ||\n|-\n| 1951 || ''[[Sins of Madeleine]]'' || Malou ||\n|-\n| 1951 || ''[[Paris Still Sings]]'' || Gis\u00e8le ||\n|-\n| 1952 || ''Fortun\u00e9 de Marseille'' || Tonia ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''L'\u00e9trange amazone'' || Eliane ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''Mandat d'amener'' || Fran\u00e7oise Delanglade ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''[[L\u00e9g\u00e8re et court v\u00eatue]]'' (''Lightly and Shortly Dressed'') || Jacqueline Lorette / Kiki ||\n|-\n| 1953 || ''L'aventuri\u00e8re du Tchad '' (''[[The Adventurer of Chad]]'') || Fanny Lacour ||\n|-\n| 1954 || ''Si Versailles m'\u00e9tait cont\u00e9'' (''[[Royal Affairs in Versailles]]'') || Une dame de la cour || Uncredited\n|-\n| 1954 || ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Quai des blondes|fr}}'' || Nelly ||\n|-\n| 1954 || ''Cadet Rousselle'' || Marguerite de Beaufort ||\n|-\n| 1955 || ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1955 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'' || Emilie Pellapra ||\n|-\n| 1955 || ''La p\u00edcara molinera'' || Jacqueline ||\n|-\n| 1956 || ''Le pays d'o\u00f9 je viens'' (''The Country I Come From'') || Adrienne Terreau ||\n|-\n| 1957 || ''[[La Parisienne (film)|La Parisienne]]''|| Monique Wilson ||\n|-\n| 1958 || ''[[La Vie \u00e0 deux]]'' (''Life for Two'') || Peggy ||\n|-\n| 1959 || ''Vous n'avez rien \u00e0 d\u00e9clarer?'' || Gloria Frontignac ||\n|-\n| 1959 || ''Le chemin des \u00e9coliers'' (''[[Way of Youth]]'') || Flora ||\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[8\u00bd]]'' || Madeleine, the French actress ||\n|-\n| 1964 || ''[[Desaf\u00edo en R\u00edo Bravo]]'' (''Gunmen of the Rio Grande'') || Jennie Lee ||\n|-\n| 1964 || ''[[Ang\u00e9lique, Marquise des Anges]]'' || La Grande Demoiselle ||\n|-\n| 1965 || ''La vuelta'' || ||\n|-\n| 1967 || ''La bouqueti\u00e8re des innocents'' || Marie de M\u00e9dicis || TV movie\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{AllMovie name}}\n* {{TCMDb name|110551}}\n* {{BFI|4ce2ba26f3e0e}}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lebeau, Madeleine}}\n[[Category:1923 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:French film actresses]]\n[[Category:French expatriates in Spain]]\n[[Category:People from Antony, Hauts-de-Seine]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Spain]]\n[[Category:French expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Orangemike", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madeleine_Lebeau"}
{"title_page": "Agaricus dulcidulus", "text_new": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Agaricus dulcidulus 001.jpg\n| image_width = 234px\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Agaricales]]\n| familia = [[Agaricaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Agaricus]]''\n| species = '''''A. dulcidulus'''''\n| binomial =''Agaricus dulcidulus''\n| binomial_authority = [[Stephan Schulzer von M\u00fcggenburg|Schulzer]] (1874)\n| synonyms_ref =\n| synonyms = ''Agaricus purpurellus'' <small>([[F.H.M\u00f8ller]]) F.H.M\u00f8ller</small><br>\n''Agaricus rubelloides'' <small>[[Marcel Bon|Bon]]</small><br>\n''Agaricus rubellus'' <small>([[Claude Casimir Gillet|Gillet]]) [[Sacc.]]</small><br>\n''Fungus dulcidulus'' <small>(Schulzer) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small><br>\n''Pratella rubella'' <small>Gillet</small><br>\n''Pratella silvatica'' var. ''rubella'' <small>(Gillet) L.Corb.</small><br>\n''Psalliota amethystina'' <small>sensu Lange</small><br>\n''Psalliota pallens'' <small>([[Jakob Emanuel Lange|J.E.Lange]]) [[Carleton Rea|Rea]]</small><br>\n''Psalliota purpurella'' <small>F.H.M\u00f8ller</small><br>\n''Psalliota rubella'' <small>(Gillet) Rea</small><br>\n''Psalliota rubella'' f. ''pallens'' <small>J.E.Lange</small>\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox\n| name = ''Agaricus dulcidulus''\n| whichGills =free\n| capShape =convex\n| capShape2=flat\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter=ring\n| ecologicalType=saprotrophic\n| sporePrintColor=brown\n| sporePrintColor2=\n| howEdible=edible\n}}\n\n'''''Agaricus dulcidulus''''' is a small [[mushroom]] in the family [[Agaricaceae]] of the [[order (biology)|order]] [[Agaricales]], found in [[deciduous forest|deciduous woodlands]] of [[Europe]], but also recorded in [[North America]], [[North Africa]] and [[Asia]]. The English name is '''rosy wood mushroom'''. Despite the tendency of some sources to [[synonym (biology)|synonymize]] it with ''[[Agaricus semotus]]'', this is a distinct taxon.<ref>''Agaricus dulcidulus'' page at [[Index Fungorum]]</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n[[Pileus (mycology)|Cap]] 2 to 7&nbsp;cm, convex-rounded often with inflexed margins at first, then flattens when aging, covered in purple-brown to pinkish dense fibriles that fade in colours towards light grayish-pink from the centre towards margins.<ref>Saccardo, P.A.(1887)'' Sylloge Fungorum V'': 1007; XIX: 32; XII: 90</ref>\n\nThe [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] are free from attachment to the stipe, dense, starting pale gray-brownish when young, then turning dark purple-brown with age, with a lighter crenulated edge. The [[Stipe (mycology)|stipe]] is cylindrical, 2\u20135&nbsp;cm long and 0.4\u20130.8&nbsp;cm broad, bulbous or clavated at the base, withish, slightly darkening toward the base in yellow-brownish tints. The [[annulus (mycology)|ring]], remnant of the veil present in young fructifications, is whitish, descendent, thin and fragile. The odor and taste resembles almonds.\n\nThe [[spore print]] is dark brownish. The [[spores]] are 4.5\u20136.0 x 3.5\u20134.0&nbsp;\u03bcm on average, [[nonamyloid]], and elliptical. The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] turns slightly in yellow when cut or bruised, sometime with orange tints in [[Stipe (mycology)|stipe]].\n\nMacrochemical reactions: flesh turns orange and [[pileus (mycology)|pileus]] turns yellow in contact with 10% [[KOH test|KOH]].\n\n==Other taxonomic considerations==\n\nSeveral characteristics like flesh yellowing on contact or in air, orange reaction with KOH, overall size, puts this species within ''Minores'' [[section (biology)|section]] of the genus ''[[Agaricus]]'', along with ''[[Agaricus comtulus]]'', ''[[Agaricus xantholepis]]'', ''[[Agaricus porphyrizon]]'' and ''[[Agaricus luteomaculatus]]''.\n\n==Habitat==\n\n'''''Agaricus dulcidulus''''' is a [[mycorrhiza]]l species in close relation with different [[oak]] species.<ref>LENTI, Istv\u00e1n. ''MUSHROOMS LIVING AMONG US: MUSHROOMS\u2013WORLD OF B\u00c1TORLIGET'' at 7th INTERNATIONAL MULTIDISCIPLINARY CONFERENCE Baia Mare, Romania, May 17\u201318, 2007, p. 409</ref> The fungus prefers humid soil with rich decomposed leaves as a [[substrate (biology)|substrate]]. The basidiocarps appear, depending on microclimatic conditions, in late July to early October.\n\n==Edibility==\nAlthough considered to be [[edible mushroom|edible]], the small size and usually the sporadic presence prevents it from being widely eaten.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Fungi}}\n*[[List of Agaricus species|List of ''Agaricus'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4691341}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agaricus Dulcidulus}}\n[[Category:Agaricus|dulcidulus]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1874]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Africa]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Fungi of North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Taxobox\n| image = Agaricus dulcidulus 001.jpg\n| image_width = 234px\n| regnum = [[Fungi]]\n| divisio = [[Basidiomycota]]\n| classis = [[Agaricomycetes]]\n| ordo = [[Agaricales]]\n| familia = [[Agaricaceae]]\n| genus = ''[[Agaricus]]''\n| species = '''''A. dulcidulus'''''\n| binomial =''Agaricus dulcidulus''\n| binomial_authority = [[Stephan Schulzer von M\u00fcggenburg|Schulzer]] (1874)\n| synonyms_ref =\n| synonyms = ''Agaricus purpurellus'' <small>([[F.H.M\u00f8ller]]) F.H.M\u00f8ller</small><br>\n''Agaricus rubelloides'' <small>[[Marcel Bon|Bon]]</small><br>\n''Agaricus rubellus'' <small>([[Claude Casimir Gillet|Gillet]]) [[Sacc.]]</small><br>\n''Fungus dulcidulus'' <small>(Schulzer) [[Otto Kuntze|Kuntze]]</small><br>\n''Pratella rubella'' <small>Gillet</small><br>\n''Pratella silvatica'' var. ''rubella'' <small>(Gillet) L.Corb.</small><br>\n''Psalliota amethystina'' <small>sensu Lange</small><br>\n''Psalliota pallens'' <small>([[Jakob Emanuel Lange|J.E.Lange]]) [[Carleton Rea|Rea]]</small><br>\n''Psalliota purpurella'' <small>F.H.M\u00f8ller</small><br>\n''Psalliota rubella'' <small>(Gillet) Rea</small><br>\n''Psalliota rubella'' f. ''pallens'' <small>J.E.Lange</small>\n}}\n{{mycomorphbox\n| name = ''Agaricus dulcidulus''\n| whichGills =free\n| capShape =convex\n| capShape2=flat\n| hymeniumType=gills\n| stipeCharacter=ring\n| ecologicalType=saprotrophic\n| sporePrintColor=brown\n| sporePrintColor2=\n| howEdible=edible\n}}\n\n'''''Agaricus dulcidulus''''' is a small sized [[mushroom]] belonging to the [[Agaricales]] [[Order (biology)|order]], family [[Agaricaceae]], growing in [[deciduous forest|deciduous woodlands]] of [[Europe]], but also recorded in [[North America]], [[North Africa]] and [[Asia]]. The English name is '''rosy wood mushroom'''. Despite the tendency of some sources to [[synonym (biology)|synonymize]] it with ''[[Agaricus semotus]]'', this is a distinct taxon.<ref>''Agaricus dulcidulus'' page at [[Index Fungorum]]</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n[[Pileus (mycology)|Cap]] 2 to 7&nbsp;cm, convex-rounded often with inflexed margins at first, then flattens when aging, covered in purple-brown to pinkish dense fibriles that fade in colours towards light grayish-pink from the centre towards margins.<ref>Saccardo, P.A.(1887)'' Sylloge Fungorum V'': 1007; XIX: 32; XII: 90</ref>\n\nThe [[lamella (mycology)|gills]] are free from attachment to the stipe, dense, starting pale gray-brownish when young, then turning dark purple-brown with age, with a lighter crenulated edge. The [[Stipe (mycology)|stipe]] is cylindrical, 2\u20135&nbsp;cm long and 0.4\u20130.8&nbsp;cm broad, bulbous or clavated at the base, withish, slightly darkening toward the base in yellow-brownish tints. The [[annulus (mycology)|ring]], remnant of the veil present in young fructifications, is whitish, descendent, thin and fragile. The odor and taste resembles almonds.\n\nThe [[spore print]] is dark brownish. The [[spores]] are 4.5\u20136.0 x 3.5\u20134.0&nbsp;\u03bcm on average, [[nonamyloid]], and elliptical. The [[trama (mycology)|flesh]] turns slightly in yellow when cut or bruised, sometime with orange tints in [[Stipe (mycology)|stipe]].\n\nMacrochemical reactions: flesh turns orange and [[pileus (mycology)|pileus]] turns yellow in contact with 10% [[KOH test|KOH]].\n\n==Other taxonomic considerations==\n\nSeveral characteristics like flesh yellowing on contact or in air, orange reaction with KOH, overall size, puts this species within ''Minores'' [[section (biology)|section]] of the genus ''[[Agaricus]]'', along with ''[[Agaricus comtulus]]'', ''[[Agaricus xantholepis]]'', ''[[Agaricus porphyrizon]]'' and ''[[Agaricus luteomaculatus]]''.\n\n==Habitat==\n\n'''''Agaricus dulcidulus''''' is a [[mycorrhiza]]l species in close relation with different [[oak]] species.<ref>LENTI, Istv\u00e1n. ''MUSHROOMS LIVING AMONG US: MUSHROOMS\u2013WORLD OF B\u00c1TORLIGET'' at 7th INTERNATIONAL MULTIDISCIPLINARY CONFERENCE Baia Mare, Romania, May 17\u201318, 2007, p. 409</ref> The fungus prefers humid soil with rich decomposed leaves as a [[substrate (biology)|substrate]]. The basidiocarps appear, depending on microclimatic conditions, in late July to early October.\n\n==Edibility==\nAlthough considered to be [[edible mushroom|edible]], the small size and usually the sporadic presence prevents it from being widely eaten.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Fungi}}\n*[[List of Agaricus species|List of ''Agaricus'' species]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q4691341}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Agaricus Dulcidulus}}\n[[Category:Agaricus|dulcidulus]]\n[[Category:Fungi described in 1874]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Africa]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Asia]]\n[[Category:Fungi of Europe]]\n[[Category:Fungi of North America]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Agaricus_dulcidulus"}
